nprofile can be scaled by the depth against the bulldozer to collapse data from\ndifferent times, radial positions and experiments onto common master curves\nthat are characteristic of the granular material and depend on the local Froude\nnumber. The lateral profile of the dune along the face of the bulldozer varies\nmore gradually with radial position, and evolves by slow lateral spreading. The\nspreading is asymmetrical, with the inward progress of the dune eventually\narrested and its bulk migrating to larger radii. A one-dimensional\ndepth-averaged model recovers the nearly linear perpendicular profile of the\ndune, but does not capture the finer nonlinear details of the master curves. A\ntwo-dimensional version of the model leads to an advection-diffusion equation\nthat reproduces the lateral spreading and radial migration.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 1 May 2014 15:13:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-05-02"}
